Business Analytics Final Project: Predictive Analysis of Stroke

Yijie He

2024-02-13

1. Statement of Research Objectives

According to the World Health Organization (WHO) data, stroke is the second leading cause of death globally, accounting for approximately 11% of the total deaths.

Our research aims to harness machine learning to predict stroke occurrence, focusing on the impact of various health indicators. The objective is to identify key predictive variables that contribute to stroke risk, thereby enhancing early intervention strategies.

2. Background and Preparation

In preparation for our study, we conducted an extensive literature review(need to add some literature here) focused on identifying factors that may contribute to the onset of stroke. Subsequently, we selected a comprehensive stroke dataset from Kaggle, specifically chosen for its robust set of variables and their relevance to our predictive objectives.

3. Methodology

Our approach involved rigorous data cleaning to ensure accuracy, followed by comprehensive data visualization to identify patterns and anomalies. We utilized logistic regression as our primary statistical technique, enabling us to model the probability of stroke events based on multiple predictors.

3.1 Descriptive Analysis

3.1.1 Overview of data we used

The dataset comprises 5110 observations and 12 variables. Excluding the patient identification number, there are 3 continuous variables and 8 categorical variables. To assess the effectiveness of our predictions, we have divided the dataset into a training set (3577 observations) and a test set (1577 observations). In this section of the descriptive analysis, we will conduct our analysis using the entire dataset. Below are specific details regarding the variables and data conditions

Overview of Dataset Variables
Field_Name Variable_Type Description
ID Discrete Unique identifier for each individual
gender Discrete Male, Female or Other
age Continuous Age of the patient
hypertension Discrete 0 if no hypertension, 1 if the patient has hypertension
heart_disease Discrete 0 if no heart disease, 1 if the patient has heart disease
work_type Discrete Children, Govt_job, Never_worked, Private, Self-employed
Residence_type Discrete Rural or Urban
avg_glucose_level Continuous The average glucose level of the patient
bmi Continuous Body Mass Index
smoking_status Discrete formerly smoked, never smoked, smokes, Unknown
ever_married Discrete Yes or No
stroke Discrete 1 if the patient had a stroke, otherwise 0

Here is the code used to convert the data to the correct type.

> dt=read.csv("healthcare-dataset-stroke-data.csv")
> dt$bmi=as.numeric(dt$bmi)
> dt$bmi[is.na(dt$bmi)]=mean(dt$bmi,na.rm = T)
> dt=dt[,-1]
> dt$hypertension=as.factor(dt$hypertension)
> dt$heart_disease=as.factor(dt$heart_disease)
> dt$stroke=as.factor(dt$stroke)
> dt$gender=factor(dt$gender,levels=c("Male","Female","Other"))
> dt$ever_married=as.factor(dt$ever_married)
> dt$work_type=as.factor(dt$work_type)
> dt$Residence_type=as.factor(dt$Residence_type)
> dt$smoking_status=factor(dt$smoking_status,levels=c("Unknown","never smoked","smokes","formerly smoked"))
> set.seed(123456)
> index = sample(1:5110,3577)
> dt_train=dt[index,]
> dt_test = dt[-index,]
> write.csv(dt_train,"stroke_train.csv")
> write.csv(dt_test,"stroke_test.csv")

3.1.3 Visulization

Prior to constructing our predictive model, we conducted preliminary visualizations of the continuous variables in relation to stroke occurrences to intuitively grasp any potential correlations.

Figure 2.1 and 2.2 illustrate the distribution of BMI among individuals with and without stroke. Notably, the distribution of BMI in the non-stroke group demonstrates a pronounced heavy-tailed characteristic, providing a distinct distribution feature that could be advantageous for prediction purposes. Conversely, glucose levels display a clear positive correlation with the likelihood of stroke, with higher glucose levels being associated with a greater proportion of stroke cases compared to non-stroke; however, Figure 2.4, which depicts a scatter plot of BMI against glucose levels, does not exhibit a strong correlation between the two variables within stroke/non-stroke groups, suggesting clustering.

Among the continuous variables, age showed the most significant predictive power. As seen in Figure 2.3, there is a stark contrast in the age distribution between stroke and non-stroke cohorts, with the stroke-affected population heavily concentrated in the older age bracket. Figures 2.5 and 2.6, which analyze the relationship of age with the other two continuous variables, BMI and glucose levels, in stroke versus non-stroke contexts, reveal no significant correlations. There is a slight positive relationship between glucose levels and age, which could be attributed to the higher prevalence of diabetes in middle-aged and older populations.

We could figure out that in the logistic regression, age and avg_glucose_level have significant impact on the stroke. But we also notice that there are a lot of statistically insignificant variables. And there is multicollinearity between male and female since there is one record of other. So its time for us to do the variable choosing. We simply use step function to choose the model that fits well

step(fit)

After step function, we get a model that fits well, so we delve deeper into it The selected variables have a significant impact on the occurrence of stroke and meet the requirements of model building. These include age, average glucose level, BMI, smoking status, and type of residence. All of these factors have a significant correlation with the occurrence of stroke. Among them, age, average glucose level, and BMI are continuous variables that are directly included in the model building. The type of residence is a categorical variable, which was converted into dummy variables for model building

fit2 = glm(formula = stroke ~ age + avg_glucose_level + hypertension + work_self + 
             work_govt + smoking_smokes, family = binomial(link = "logit"), data = train)

4.2 Sensitivity and specificity check

Our accuracy is 95% if we choose a cutoff of 0.5, but all of our prediction is false, which is meaningless in the field of health diagonostics. So we find out the best cutoff level is 0.035 through trial and error. During this cutoff level, our sensitivity is 89.01% and specificity is 66.01%

Here is the trial and error process. First we want to draw a ROC graph to have a basic understanding of the range of a good threshold

library(InformationValue)

conf_matrix_list <- list(
  "Threshold 0.05" = confusionMatrix(actuals = train$stroke, predictedScores=train$estimatedstroke, threshold = 0.05),
  "Threshold 0.045" = confusionMatrix(actuals = train$stroke, predictedScores=train$estimatedstroke_mid2, threshold = 0.045),
  "Threshold 0.04" = confusionMatrix(actuals = train$stroke, predictedScores=train$estimatedstroke_mid, threshold = 0.04),
  "Threshold 0.035" = confusionMatrix(actuals = train$stroke, predictedScores=train$estimatedstroke_mid3, threshold = 0.04),
  "Threshold 0.03" = confusionMatrix(actuals = train$stroke, predictedScores=train$estimatedstroke_low, threshold = 0.04)
)

# store the output of sensitivity and specificity
results <- data.frame(
  Threshold = c(0.05, 0.04, 0.045, 0.035, 0.03),
  Sensitivity = c(
    sensitivity(actuals = train$stroke, predictedScores = train$estimatedstroke, threshold = 0.05),
    sensitivity(actuals = train$stroke, predictedScores = train$estimatedstroke_mid2, threshold = 0.045),
    sensitivity(actuals = train$stroke, predictedScores = train$estimatedstroke_mid, threshold = 0.04),
    sensitivity(actuals = train$stroke, predictedScores = train$estimatedstroke_mid3, threshold = 0.035),
    sensitivity(actuals = train$stroke, predictedScores = train$estimatedstroke_low, threshold = 0.03)
  ),
  Specificity = c(
    specificity(actuals = train$stroke, predictedScores = train$estimatedstroke, threshold = 0.05),
    specificity(actuals = train$stroke, predictedScores = train$estimatedstroke_mid2, threshold = 0.045),
    specificity(actuals = train$stroke, predictedScores = train$estimatedstroke_mid, threshold = 0.04),
    specificity(actuals = train$stroke, predictedScores = train$estimatedstroke_mid3, threshold = 0.035),
    specificity(actuals = train$stroke, predictedScores = train$estimatedstroke_low, threshold = 0.03)
  )
)

5. Conclusion

Our models sensitivity of 88.15% and specificity of 69.73% suggest that the model fit is satisfactory. However, for real-world applications, we may desire a higher sensitivity. This could potentially be achieved by collecting more data or employing advanced machine learning techniques. Additionally, the geographic origin of the dataset could also influence our model, but this aspect is currently unknown.
